This started out as a quick'n'dirty hack for my printer but I've found it really useful so far.
It's a printed base with a battery, buzzer, switch and some PTFE tubing.

Your filament will run in the short PTFE tube and along the way holding the switch open, disconnecting the buzzer circuit.
As soon as your filament runs out/passes through completely, the circuit will close and the buzzer will start singing the song of it's people.

This instantly lets you know it's time to hook up a new spool!

I know you could do a more advanced version and hook it up to your controller but this is a simple add-on that works on any printer without any hacking, just put it between your spool and extruder and you're good to go!

Hardware needed:
9V battery
Micro-switch
Some wire
PTFE tubing
2x M3 screws for the switch

Notes:

Printed in ABS.
Two layers top and bottom for links.
Four layers top and bottoms for buttons so that they would be mostly solid.
Print "links 1" and "button" in first color.
Print "links 2" and "button" in second color.

Assembley

Place the links in order and then thread the monofiliment line through them one way, then through the holes in one button, then back through the links the other way. Cut the line leaving enough to tie, thread both ends through the second button, and tie knot while pulling line taught.

I had printed http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:31253 but found with my print the pins didn't hold the links tight enough for the snake to hold shape. Recalled Rubik's Magic used monofiliament and thought it might work for this as well, which it does fairly well.
Designed this in AutoCAD 123D. Used Simplify3D for gcode.

description.text:
This is a door release button for a Panasonic NNSD277B/W microwave.
I bought the microwave a little over two years ago. Since then, I've had both plastic retention tabs at the side of the button fail, and ordered a replacement part. 
After a little over a year, one of the replacement part's tabs has already snapped off and the other is sure to follow soon.
I decided to reverse engineer the part in FreeCAD today before the other tab breaks off (they get lost inside the microwave making them virtually impossible to retrieve) and share it here in the event I need to print myself off a copy at some point in the future.
Panasonic: Shame on you for designing such a crummy part and charging your customers ~$50 to replace it every ~18 months.
For production with a 3D printer or 3D printing service.

First I want to say that I designed this thing with the greatest respect and gratefulness for http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:537918 which made many a good print possible in the first place.

And still... Experiencing the limitationes of my equipment and with increasing expectationes of my prints I had some serious cooling issues.
This thing is designed for maximum airflow onto the object using common or even existing 40mm fans. Due to the overhangs printing it the first time without any active cooling one should use cool air of a hair-dryer or similar for a proper print. A common 40mm fan fits snug without screws depending on how well your printer is dialed in. Same for the brackets. Certainly there is need of reworking the hexagons to fit these little gizmos.
It is no remix but a completely new design from scratch but certainly orientated on the already existing.

The purple Marvin I printed with my favorite material using the above mentioned air duct and additional (cool) hair dryer. The red one is my worst colour, somewhat overextruding and printed using the new duct. I think it shows some difference between both.

I do know that this is far away from beeing perfect, most of you guys may have way better printers. Considering the limits of my CTC equipement I am very satisfied.

description.text:
I wanted a holder for my Baofeng UV-5R two-way radio in my 1995 Jeep YJ. Since I already made an iPhone 6 holder (see http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1148280), I figured why not just make an insert for that (assuming I don't need to hold both at once).

So here it is -- it slides in to the iPhone holder and the radio belt clip goes through the hole.

Assuming you have a Jeep YJ and an iPhone 6 and a Baofeng UV-5R then this is just the thing for you!

Or, if you just want to hold your radio and you don't want the iPhone holder, I don't see any reason why you couldn't just print this part and the dashboard grabber part from the iPhone holder and glue them together without the phone holder part.

description.text:
A very simple upgrade for the SeemeCnc H1 printer is replacing the idlers for the belts with ball bearings. Using the stock bolts this means we need a sleeve to go from the 1/4" cap screw to the 8mm ID of the bearing. The bearings are cheap readily available skateboard bearings. Also known as 608 size. Measurements:
22mm OD
8mm ID
7mm height This is quite possibly the second simplest STL on thingiverse after a cal cube!

The only important thing to do is make sure it prints as just perimeters/shells, infill isn't really the way to go on something so thin. My printer had alot of backlash (therefore the part wasn't as round as intended) so I had to run a 5mm drill through after printing. Works great, print a couple at a time (I did 4) so each layer has time to cool. The 'stack' when assembled should be:
Cap screw
1/4"ID x 1-1/16"OD x 1/16"Thick Plastic Washer
idler_sleeve + skateboard bearing

1/4"ID x 1-1/16"OD x 1/16"Thick Plastic Washer
Z axis plate
10-32 Nylon Lock Nut Stainless Steel

description.text:
Jack pad for ordinary garage car jack.

I designed this primarily for our two Toyotas. An Aygo and a Verso. It's supposed to fit where you attach the emergency jack according to the "User manual".

You can't use a garage jack without a pad that fits this spot, otherwise you will damage the car.

The goal is to make it easy to switch between summer and winter wheels.

I have printed it in flexible filament to avoid damage the car body parts.

You can print this in any layer height, the finish is not very important. What to consider is the infill percentage. It will take some pressure so use a relative high infill.

I used Hobby King flexible filament. This filament is not super flexible, so you will get a fairly robust block if you are using 70% infill.

description.text:
Now has a little sibling at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2105705.

!!!DEBURR THE GEARS AND REMOVE SHARP EDGES FROM THE GEAR TEETH!!!
Do not put anything that can get hurt in to mesh point of gears!
Not for young children. If not assembled correctly, ball bearings can fall out.

Meshing helical gear fidget toy with through hole for finger.  
Printing two of the same gears will make them mesh at 90 degrees.
Printing one right hand and one left hand gear will mesh straight on same plane.
Same housing for both straight and perpendicular planes assemblies.

Included is an STL for a bearing race dressing tool.
I passed some 180 grit sand paper through the slots.
Pushed it in the the half toroids and rotated back,
and forth to help smooth out ball bearing grooves.

I used PLA for the gears, and ABS for the housings.
The little holes in the housing are meant to receive short pieces of filament.
Cemented together using acetone on the ABS housings and inner cylinder.
Epoxy or any decent glue can be used to assemble the housing pieces as well.
There are a few versions of the inner cylinder.
I had delamination issues when removing it from the printing bed.
A little acetone on a paint brush re-enforced the laminations fairly well.

Spherical 4.5mm(0.177") BB ammunition is used for the ball bearings.

Contained with this package is an OpenSCAD script for generating metric helical gear blanks.
Written by yours truly, is being released under and besides this fidget toy under the GNU GPLv3 license.
I exported the gear to an STL. I then imported the STL in to TurboCAD, and carved out the rest.

If the assembly meshes a little tight, you might try
    1.  Scaling a difference of up to 0.5% between housing and the gear(make the housing bigger). 
        More than that, and housing might "rock" over the ball bearings.
    2.  Printing shim to your desired thickness, and adding to the housing assembly.
        In CURA the shim can be cut off to the desired thickness.
        Something is very wrong if you need more than 1mm.
    3.  Included are two gears.  One is to spec with no backlash.
        The other has 5% of the CP removed from the gear profile for added 
        backlash(clearance on the gear tooth flank). This one is loose.

If anyone wants a copy of the original TurboCAD files, or an export to AutoCAD DWG,
please make your request in the comment section.  I'll zip it up and post it.

Bill Of Materials for pair of meshing gears
    4 housings
    2 inner cylinders
    2 gears
    4 short pieces of filament ~9mm long.
    BB Balls to fill grooves
    Glue or Acetone(ABS)

title: Doctor Who Tardis-Bookend with LED-lighting
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A tardis bookend I'm currently designing for the 50th Anniversary of our favourite timey-wimey TV Show.   
It features the TARDIS including a working blinking light on top and a little bit of lighting for the "inside".

Cut and engrave the parts from the following material to recreate the version I'm building:
2x tardis_blue_cut. + tardis_blue_engraved. from 3mm blue translucent acrylic
1x tardis_white_cut. from 3mm white translucent acrylic.
1x tardis_lamp_cut. + 1x tardis_lamp_engraved. from 3mm transparent acrylic
2x tardis_white_outer. + 2x tardis_white_engraved.* from 3mm white translucent acrylic Note: the idea behind engraving the white acrylic, is to provide a rough surface, where permanent marker, can stick well, no idea if this is necessary. -But for any other color than white, the engraving files should be useful. UPDATE: I now use a heavy engraving with 50% depth and fill the resulting channels with black window-color instead of using a permanent marker. PS: The image shown, is still missing the base and side of the bookend, as well as the LEDs.
Also the middle pane is supposed to be cut from white translucent acrylic instead of the blue one used here.
However, I simply couldn't find the material in any home-improvement store nearby.
  • You should of course cut and engrave this from white acrylic.

Normally you should use GoPro original app (GoPro Studio) but since it works ONLY with synced via original orange cable footage you will not be able to get automatic sync, and this way is closed for us. So i use Adobe After Effects for syncing and color correction. Basically all you should do is to drop both footages (left and right) on a timeline, find some noticeable audio-peak on both audio tracks and align them as close as you can (minor shift in frame or half frame is ok, and i never saw 100% alignment )) )
After you align footage on timeline clip both clips and do what you want (i.e. cut, color-correct, etc.)
Important things not to miss:
1) while shooting - clap your hands 2-3 times near the camera - you will get nice noticeable audio peaks at the start
2) try not to swap left and right footage )) - or you will get strange headache while watching it on a TV ))

title: Pitot Tube Mini-Mount

description.text:
After printing several Pitot tube mounts and finding them all too big and obtrusive, I decided to go the minimalist approach and create one that will mount under the leading edge of the wing or on the side of the fuselage nose. It is a two piece print that will accomodate many of the all metal pitot tubes sold by most FPV suppliers. A drawing of the metal pitot tube I used for this is included for reference.

To install, simply trace the outline of the mount base under the wing where the leading edge angle keeps the tube level (about 18mm back on my Mini Talon). Next, carve a shallow area inside the marks and glue the base in. Then use thin servo tape or rubber glue to mount the pitot tube in the tube mount and snap on the mount cover. Now you need to run the hoses slightly in-laid into the wing to where you want the sensor. I will use nylon antenna wire tubing for this.

This is a spring designed to reduce the stiffness of the thumbwheel tensioner system to make the pressure on the filament and drive wheel more consistent.
The spring is designed to be made from 1.6mm 2024-T3 Aluminium
I have FEA'd it to check stiffness (about 40N/mm) and yield strength (more than sufficient, I think!)

Using the supplied flat pattern .dxf, cut the profile from 1.6mm 2024-T3  Aluminium sheet or similar.  
(Note, steel, stainless steel etc will probably be too stiff and difficult to work, unless you make it from thinner sheet)
The sheet is bent (according to the bend lines in the .dxf file) with an internal bend radius of 3mm.  When correctly bent, the distance between the mounting flange edge and the plate where the thumb screw goes through is about 1mm
You will need to remove the two screws that retain the thumbscrew nut.  The spring should be installed on the four (of six) bolts that hold the drive assembly together.  The thumbscrew nut hex is allowed to run flush with the edge of the drive assembly.

description.text:
Charging dock for Lightning compatible devices. The dock is an exact copy of Apple's iPhone Lightning Dock with the exception that it charges the iPhone and Apple Watch at the same time via Micro USB rather than a Lightning connector.

There are two versions of this dock, one with a watch charger and one without.

The Phone dock will charge and sync the phone via any USB port but the Phone & Watch dock will only charge both devices when connected to a 2.1A charging USB port (This limitation could probably be overcome by creating two voltage dividers for the watch charger's data+ and - lines).

Press an Apple Lightning to USB Cable into the top of the dock (I used an old damaged cable), remove the USB Type-A connector and solder the wires to the Micro USB Breakout Board. The breakout board can then be pressed into the bottom of the dock. Place Adhesive Backed Lead Weights into the side cavities on the dock's underside (Do not skip this step if you are making the Phone & Watch dock as it will tip over without the added weight!).

For the Apple Watch dock remove the USB Type-A connector from your Apple Watch Magnetic Charging Cable and insert it into the watch dock. Bend 5mm Brass Tubing at 90° with a Tube Bender. Trim both sides of the tube using an X-ACTO knife making sure it's not so long as to tip the dock over due to the watch's weight. Run the watch charger's cable through the tube until the tube presses into the watch dock. Press the other side of the tube into the phone dock and flare the edge to fasten the tube in place. Solder the watch charger's wires to the micro USB breakout board.

Secure the parts together with acrylate glue if needed. then glue the bottom grip to the underside of the dock.

description.text: A checkerboard on a hinged box. The pieces are stored inside.

First, I made the board on Adobe. The board is 11.5 x 11.5 inches. I then used www.boxmake.rahulbotics.com to create the box design. The box is 11.5 x 11.5 inches and 3 inches in depth. Because of the boxes puzzle piece like edges, I had to flatten the top edge using a straight line. I did this so that the checkerboard itself would lay flat on top. Next, I measured medium hinges and placed holes on the board and side where i wanted them to go. The holes must be exact so that the hinges fit correctly. I also made the pieces using Adobe. I made 1.3 inch circles. 32 pieces are needed in all. 16 of each color. 24 of them are not engraved, and 8 of them are. The 8 have kings crowns on them so that they can represent a king in the game. Once I finished all of these designs I printed them using the Epilog Laser.  I used 3mm acrylic. All of my vector speeds were 10, power 100, and frequency 5000. My raster speed was 100 and the power was set to 60. I then assembled the box using acrylic glue. To fasten each hinge hole I used a screw, small nut, washer, and bolt.

title: MakerGear M2 Filament RunOut Switch bracket

description.text:
This is a simple Micro-switch filament run-out sensor built into the filament guide bracket for the MakerGear M2.

I used the old Z endstop micro-switch and LED from the M2, as I have replaced the Z endstop with an inductive probe. In order to get the LED to light up when out of filament, I de-soldered the ground side of the led from the center pin, and soldered it to the unused pin.

You will need to modify your firmware to enable the run-out sensor to trigger the M600 command, and your firmware will need to have support for it.

I currently use Marin V1.1.0 RC7. To add this, you will need to enable
"#define FILAMENT_RUNOUT_SENSOR" in Configuration.H
as well, the logic needs to be reversed if set up the same way the MakerGear M2 Endstops are you do this in the linee "const bool FIL_RUNOUT_INVERTING = true;"

You will need to enable;
"#define FILAMENT_CHANGE_FEATURE" in Configuration_adv.H

You will also need to add a pin Definition to the Pins.H file (pins_RAMBO.h for me)
(my printer is running with a RAMBo 1.3, and I used the Z max endstop connection, so the line I added to it was "#define FIL_RUNOUT_PIN 30"
